<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<qti-assessment-item
    xmlns="http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/imsqtiasi_v3p0"
    xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
    xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/imsqtiasi_v3p0 https://purl.imsglobal.org/spec/qti/v3p0/schema/xsd/imsqti_asiv3p0p1_v1p0.xsd http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML https://purl.imsglobal.org/spec/mathml/v3p0/schema/xsd/mathml3.xsd"
    identifier="public-trust-in-government-trend"
    title="Public Trust in Government Trend"
    time-dependent="false"
    xml:lang="en-US">

    <qti-response-declaration base-type="identifier" cardinality="single" identifier="RESPONSE">
        <qti-correct-response>
            <qti-value>A</qti-value>
        </qti-correct-response>
    </qti-response-declaration>


    <qti-outcome-declaration identifier="SCORE" cardinality="single" base-type="float">
        <qti-default-value>
            <qti-value>0</qti-value>
        </qti-default-value>
    </qti-outcome-declaration>
    <qti-outcome-declaration identifier="FEEDBACK" cardinality="single" base-type="identifier"/>
    <qti-outcome-declaration identifier="FEEDBACK-INLINE" cardinality="single" base-type="identifier"/>

    <qti-item-body>
        <p>Use the graph below to answer the following question.</p>
        <p><strong>Public trust in government</strong></p>
        <div id="reference_text">
            <img src="https://cdn.kastatic.org/ka-perseus-images/944ea7b952f01ffd1712043591fe2f0e7f55c77f.png" width="1392" height="910" alt="Public trust in government graph"/>
            <blockquote>
                <p>Source: <a href="http://www.people-press.org/2017/05/03/public-trust-in-government-1958-2017/#chart">Pew Research Center</a></p>
            </blockquote>
        </div>
        <qti-choice-interaction response-identifier="RESPONSE" shuffle="true" max-choices="1">
            <qti-prompt>Which of the following accurately describes a trend of public trust in the federal government from 1958 to 2017?</qti-prompt>
            <qti-simple-choice identifier="A">
                Public trust has generally declined, rising briefly during periods of economic growth and the 9/11 crisis
                <qti-feedback-inline outcome-identifier="FEEDBACK-INLINE" identifier="A">Based on the moving average from multiple polls the decline is clearly evident in the graph.</qti-feedback-inline>
            </qti-simple-choice>
            <qti-simple-choice identifier="B">
                The moving average of trust levels has had greater variations than the trust levels derived from individual polls
                <qti-feedback-inline outcome-identifier="FEEDBACK-INLINE" identifier="B">The moving average generally shows smaller variations in public trust over time than does the line plotted from individual polls.</qti-feedback-inline>
            </qti-simple-choice>
            <qti-simple-choice identifier="C">
                Public trust has increased during wartime administrations when the nation's citizens have rallied around the president
                <qti-feedback-inline outcome-identifier="FEEDBACK-INLINE" identifier="C">The public trust dropped during the Vietnam war era of the Johnson and Nixon administrations as well as during the invasion of Iraq during G.W. Bush's tenure.</qti-feedback-inline>
            </qti-simple-choice>
            <qti-simple-choice identifier="D">
                Public trust has declined during Democratic presidencies and has risen during Republican administrations
                <qti-feedback-inline outcome-identifier="FEEDBACK-INLINE" identifier="D">There are notable exceptions to this generalization, including the Nixon, Ford, Clinton, and both Bush presidencies.</qti-feedback-inline>
            </qti-simple-choice>
        </qti-choice-interaction>
        
        <qti-feedback-block outcome-identifier="FEEDBACK" identifier="CORRECT" show-hide="show">
            <qti-content-body>
                <p><strong>Correct!</strong> The graph clearly shows a general downward trend in public trust from around <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>75</mn><mo>%</mo></math> in 1958 to around <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>20</mn><mo>%</mo></math> in 2017, with temporary increases during periods of economic prosperity and national crises like 9/11.</p>
            </qti-content-body>
        </qti-feedback-block>
        <qti-feedback-block outcome-identifier="FEEDBACK" identifier="INCORRECT" show-hide="show">
            <qti-content-body>
                <p><strong>Not quite.</strong> Look at the overall trend from 1958 to 2017. The moving average shows trust declining from about <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>75</mn><mo>%</mo></math> to <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>20</mn><mo>%</mo></math>, with only brief increases during specific events like economic booms or national crises.</p>
            </qti-content-body>
        </qti-feedback-block>
    </qti-item-body>

    <qti-response-processing>
        <qti-response-condition>
            <qti-response-if>
                <qti-match>
                    <qti-variable identifier="RESPONSE"/>
                    <qti-correct identifier="RESPONSE"/>
                </qti-match>
                <qti-set-outcome-value identifier="SCORE">
                    <qti-base-value base-type="float">1</qti-base-value>
                </qti-set-outcome-value>
                <qti-set-outcome-value identifier="FEEDBACK">
                    <qti-base-value base-type="identifier">CORRECT</qti-base-value>
                </qti-set-outcome-value>
            </qti-response-if>
            <qti-response-else>
                <qti-set-outcome-value identifier="SCORE">
                    <qti-base-value base-type="float">0</qti-base-value>
                </qti-set-outcome-value>
                <qti-set-outcome-value identifier="FEEDBACK">
                    <qti-base-value base-type="identifier">INCORRECT</qti-base-value>
                </qti-set-outcome-value>
            </qti-response-else>
        </qti-response-condition>
    </qti-response-processing>

</qti-assessment-item>
